ht be going. The book provides a strategic window onto social theory based on current research, examining trends in classical traditions and the cutting edge of more recent approaches. From distinctive theoretical positions, contributors address questions about how social order is accomplished; the role of materiality, practice, and meaning; as well as the conditions for the knowledge of the social world. The theoretical traditions presented include cultural sociology, microsociologies, world-system theory and post-colonial theory, gender and feminism, actor network and network theory, systems theory, field theory, rational choice, poststructuralism, pragmatism, and the sociology of conventions. Each chapter introduces a tradition and presents an agenda for further theoretical development. Social Theory Now is an essential tool for sociologists. It will be central to the discussion and teaching of contemporary social theory for years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aepistemology.  afeminism.  amateriality.  ameaning.  apost-colonial theory.  apractice.  ascience.  asocial order.  asocial theory.  asociological theory.1 aAriail Reed, Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaecker, Dirk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenzecry, Claudio E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenzecry, Claudio E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErikson, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErmakoff, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeva, Dorit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGo, Julian, econtr